In addressing the members of one’s own family it was customary to add Suo (or Suae), e.g. Tullius Terentiae Suae S. P.⁸ (ie. salutem plurimam). After this address there often appeared some formula like si vales, bene est, either written out in full or in the abbreviation s. v. b. e. or s. o. b. (ie. berust).⁸ Cicero himself rarely used this formula.¹⁰
